segments.text: We're at the residence of Doris Davis in Houston.
Doris has been a force in the planning of Houston for several years, and she will begin by telling us briefly about her background before she got to Texas.
To begin at the beginning in my career in planning, I guess it was 1967 I decided to go to graduate school
in urban planning, and I did that at Wayne State University.
Why did you decide to go to planning school?
That's an interesting question.

Basically, I had a bachelor's degree in psychology and sociology, and I was then married to a clinical psychologist, and I wanted to, I had been working, doing social research work at the university, and I wanted to get a master's, and all I knew was that I didn't want to do anything like anyone I knew was doing, and I didn't know anyone who was an urban planner.
And of course having been born and bred in Brooklyn, New York, I had a great interest in urban areas.
So it was kind of one of those strange decisions that I didn't want to be anything else and that sounded good.
So you sort of backed into it?
Very much so, very much so.
I think many of us did that.
Shortly before I finished my degree, I went to work for a small consulting firm, and as you probably realize, that's where you learn how to be a planner is when you start working at it.

And then the next several years, I worked at another, one of the first non-profit consulting firms around, and we did a lot of work for money, and we did a lot of work for free, and it all evened out and was very interesting.
Uh-huh.

I also taught at the Wayne County Community College where we had a two-year program that offered a degree in planning technology at that period of time when we saw planning as a profession that had no end and that felt there would be a great need for technicians and assistants to professional planners.
I have no idea now what happened to that program.
In 1973, I moved to Houston.
had taken a job at the medical center here and proceeded to attempt to find employment.
Interestingly, I had a lot of difficulty feeling that I had a pretty good background in planning.
That was the very thing that seemed to make it hard to find a job.
There was a fair amount of suspicion and concern about a northern planner that knew all about zoning and that sort of thing, and that I would try to maybe instill some of these northern concepts
into my work here.
Early March 1st, as a matter of fact, of 1974, I did go to work for the Council of Governments.
I was hired there as an environmental planner, which was some interesting since that hadn't, to that point, been my background at all.
However, I had a strong background in demographics and land use and, in fact, my initial assignments were to work in demographics and land use for
Environmental planning is a backup to that.
I do remember when you were an environmental planner.
That's when we got to know each other first.

Well, that was my evolution, in a way, at HGAC was that whenever I would decide that I was sort of bored and it was time to move on, some opportunity would come up and I would find a whole new area to work in.
And ultimately, as you know, before I left there,

I was manager of community and environmental planning, and that had taken our environmental program, our community development, economic development program, and our information program, which was the demographics and land use, and pulled them all together into what was really pretty much a comprehensive planning department.
Doris, how do you perceive the
How would you characterize planning in Houston when you got here?
Well, it was a bad word.

The very first sort of professional planning meeting I attended in Houston, even before I found a job, I'll never forget, it was at Rice University, and the keynote speaker was then Mayor Louis Welch.
And he stood up and announced to the audience that Houston had no need of planners.
Houston was doing fine growing wild.
And this was, I see, so that you felt that the environment was not particularly supportive.
Definitely.
There was, almost appeared to be concern about planners, and in fact when I went to work at the Council of Government, there was almost concern that I was a professional planner.
And although they portrayed themselves as a regional planning agency, at the time,
that I started work, I think I was the second person there that had a bona fide urban planning master's degree in urban planning.
Now, from your knowledge of planning in the Houston area in general, how do you see it functioning in terms of, well, let's characterize it first, long-range planning and then day-to-day planning?
And planning administration, you probably have had sufficient contact with city hall to have some view of that.
And you might concentrate first on either that or HGAC, whatever you choose, and then go from there.
Well, in a way, I see them as separate things.
Let's keep them separately.
If you look at the city of Houston, per se, in planning, from the first time I've been
worked with them to this day.
Planning is very fragmented.
Every department has their own planning function, and they don't share it.

And I would say in the last few years that the planning and development department has perhaps brought in a little more on those plans, but not to any great extent, so that Public Works tends to do planning.
And in fact, all of the big money that has been spent in demographics has been spent out of Public Works.
being caught for population forecasts for various plans that they do.
The health department does planning.
The solid waste department does planning.
So that it's not the concept of comprehensive planning is really sort of alien in the city.
Although, again, in recent years, I think there have been more efforts to think in terms of a comprehensive plan.
mid-75, I guess the city had done some, I can't think of what it was called, it was Houston 2000 or something like that, which was, as I remember, consisted of a land use map of future land use.
Yeah, I have a copy of that.
Okay.
There was, and when I was initially doing demographics, my first few years at HGAC, it wasn't
to understanding of the political environment, there were many clashes, say, with City Hall in our visions of what the future growth would be like.

And I, coming from the dense urban cities of the North, tended to see kind of centralized growth, particularly since there was so much land in which that could occur, whereas the view of city planning, which was the view of City Hall,
was spread it out as far as possible and worry about the repercussions later.
And there have been repercussions.
The city was just hit with a half a million dollar fine for wastewater violations.
And in 1974, when I was hired, it was because there were wastewater concerns in the area.
And the city then was under notice that they would be enforced against.
During that period of time, they were so busy building plants way out in the outer areas for new growth, and no efforts were made to keep the inner areas up to standards.
Well, of course, Houston has had continual problems with air pollution.
Yes, that's sort of another issue.
Yeah, and they had at one time an excellent
director of their air pollution control district, Mr. Cubedo.
Yes, he passed away.
He passed away, and we haven't heard much about it lately.
But for a while, wasn't Houston under a federal court order that restricted any new industry?
And that, again, was in the early to middle 1970s, and I remember it
quite clearly because I was very impressed by the southern way of doing business.
I believe the EPA said, you're not going to be able to grow anymore.
And Houston said, go away.
And they went away.
Which is really about the way it sized up.
And it's still a problem today.
And they are, again, facing very severe penalties for ozone pollution in particular.
So they simply said, go away, and the feds did.
Basically, that's what happened.
There was a lot of effort on the part of the Chamber of Commerce, and there was a lot of activity.
And I'm sure there were some promises made, but there wasn't a great deal of regulation or anything that I could perceive happening in support of that.
But they sort of said, everything's fine here, and no, we will not be enforced against, and so forth.
That appeared to me.
I wasn't in the midst of the happenings those days.
But in viewing them, that's what appeared to happen.
It's my understanding that most of the planning that is done in actual fact is done by developers.
Well, there is a concept of private sector planning.
And in fact, to a large extent, a great deal of very fine planning has gone on by developers.
I think the problem is when there is a conflict between the public interest and the developer's interest that private sector planning tends to fall down.
Those are some of my favorite things to discuss.
For example, if you're talking about zoning, can't you accomplish the same ends in the way the developer did by providing land uses that were only compatible
or patterns that were only compatible to certain sorts of development.
You don't put a gas station in the middle of a cul-de-sac, for example.
And that was a way of planning that can work.
It's when the two interests really separate that the problems exist.
Okay.
How is the...
city planning department organized?
Today.
Well, when you first got here.
When I first got here, and I don't know that I'm the right person to speak to this, my sense was that the greatest city planning appeared to do two things.
One was to keep track of data, land use and changes, and to try to forecast the future, and the other
was to work with developers on subdivisions and plants.
I never had a sense of any sort of overall comprehensive planning.
Today, the planning department has many more responsibilities than they had then.
Community development under the Community Development Block Grant is part of the planning department.
The planning department's involved in economic development.

they've taken on some additional functions and they are making an effort to do some comprehensive planning starting at the neighborhood level and with the idea of building a lot of neighborhood plans that then could be incorporated into a proper comprehensive plan.
This is an approach I've always referred to as cut and paste.
Well, it can be.
I think that it's, at this point in time, perhaps the only approach that's politically feasible here.
And even...

I may be sorry I say this, but the development ordinance that was passed some years ago, which is a strong planning tool in many ways, appeared to come out of city council rather than out of the planning department.
Who administers the deed restrictions that have to do with the use of land?
Does the planning department have any role in this?
Not that I know of.
The only role, it's a private...
And the city some years ago felt it had, and I believe it was challenged in the courts, and indeed they had a legal right to assist in upholding the restrictions.
As far as I know, that would be city legal.
So a subdivision that was having a problem keeping their restrictions enforced, or if someone tried to do something else, could go to city legal for assistance.
And I'm not positive about the way that works.
I can find out.
OK. You got here during Roscoe Jones' tenure as planning director.
Yes.
Who was the executive director of HGAC when you got here?

When I got here, it was Royal Hatch, who was a retired brigadier general from the Air Force and had another career since and was working as, I believe he was chairman of the Gulf Coast Waste Disposal Authority before he came to HGAC.
He'd only been there less than a year when I went to work there.
What was his style of leadership?
His style was very much trying to work with the elected officials closely and understanding the concept of regionalism.
He was very much an outside man, worked with funding agencies, worked with the city representatives and the county representatives.
an inordinate amount of time with the day-to-day technical aspects of planning.
He left that to the staff, pretty much.
And he was succeeded by whom?
Jack Steele, who had been

actually grew up in the cog business, had worked at Southeast Texas Regional Planning Commission, went to HGAC in, I believe, 73 as criminal justice manager, and had worked up to director of programs, deputy executive director, and succeeded at Royal Hatch.
And what was his management style like?
Well, his management style, and he is still there today, is very different.
He is very technically qualified in many areas.
and pays a lot of attention to the program areas rather than to the political side of things or to spending a lot of time, you know, whining and dining politicians.
Okay.
What were some of the outstanding programs of HGAC?
Well, the HJC programs have evolved considerably.
Do you want me to kind of start at the beginning?
Sure.
The COG was formed, as were most COGs, I guess, in 1966, pretty much in response to A95 and the desire locally to be part of approving and disapproving federal projects.
I think that there was a fair amount of controversy about whether to form a COG.

And Emmet Lowery, who is mayor of Texas City and was at the time and was on the committee of elected officials that was meeting, deciding whether to start a regional planning commission, says that there was just considerable disagreement.
And a big issue, and I think we may come back to this later, was how communities would be represented because the city of Houston was so big and compared to any of the other
cities and counties even, whether if it was one man, one vote, then it was the city's cog.
And if it was equal representation, not caring about population, then the city could very well get hurt in the process.
This has been a classical problem facing cogs throughout the country.
And I can understand that.
Oh, yeah.
And, for example, when I was with ABAC in the San Francisco region,
There we had two central cities, Oakland and San Francisco.
And there was a certain amount of jealousy, of course, between, and then Berkeley as a third.
So it was quite complicated.
And the same thing has happened elsewhere in the country, almost without exception.
Well, and of course, Houston was just so much bigger than any other community.
And it was agreed, though, that the other communities just weren't interested if it was going to be a Houston animal.
Houston agreed at that time that they would not take it over.
And as the, and I don't believe the board composition has changed much over the years.
When the COG was formed it was eight counties and I don't know exactly which year but about maybe two or four years later it was made into 13 counties by the state who determines the area.
And the board of directors, each county has
One position, Harris County being so large, has two.
The city of Houston has two seats, and other cities, 25,000 or over, each have a seat.
There are two seats for cities, home rule cities under 25,000, and two seats for general law cities under 25,000.
One for independent school districts, one for soil and water conservation districts, and Houston Independent School District.
That's interesting.
At ABAC, none of the school districts have representation.
Only units of general purpose government.
Well, you know, some of them don't even have school districts as members.
So even though Houston and Harris County have four seats out of 27, it doesn't allow them to have a majority or to make the decisions for the COG.

However, I think there was recognition that Houston needed in some way to work with some of the other communities, and although that may be getting ahead of myself, I really think the major thing was that they needed to have this regional planning commission in order to have a little more power over grants that came into the area.
Then, of course, with the years of 701 money, there was a natural source of funding, and it wasn't going to cost anyone particularly anything to have this animal.
I think the planning that was done then was extremely responsive to federal regulations.
It was minimal.
We'll do what we have to do to keep the money flowing, but we're not going to do too much else.
It was sort of a pipeline for money.
Exactly.
In the early years, almost all of the work of the very small staff, from what I gather, almost all the work was done by consultants.
So in addition to doing what the federal government wanted,
The actual work was done by people that understood the local interests and was, you know, quite controlled.
At the time that I went to the COG in 1974, there was still a perception that this would try to be a tool of the federal government and one had to always be cautious about it.
And I think the staff themselves were very torn all the time between

what the federal government wanted and what a trained planner might feel would be the right way to pursue a planning process, and what the local governments appeared to want, which was to leave them alone to do their own thing.
So there was a lot of conflict, I think, in early planning efforts when the staff went
too far towards what they viewed of as planning.
The board would tend to get kind of upset about it, or individual governments would.
When the staff was doing what the local governments appeared to want, the federal government wasn't very happy.

And in fact, towards the end of 701 money, I guess in 79 and 80, we had really, before the money stopped flowing, made a conscious decision that we weren't going to apply for it any longer, because we were
had so much administrative work with regard to the grant, and only a small piece of the grants were being used to do what the local governments wanted, which in those days was information.
They wanted good data.
They wanted a lot of day-to-day technical assistance and handholding, which was valid.
But they didn't want the kinds of strategic plans that HUD was beginning to require.
And the one that we did for HUD,
In fact, never got out of draft form.
The money went away, and we never had to do anything further about it.
Plans that were controversial were those that had to have local government approval in addition to just the COG doing it.
But because there was a very good flow of money, the COG in the early years did some very innovative work.
We were talking at lunch about Charles Trost, for example.
In the late 60s and early 70s, he developed some very sophisticated computer programs that we had a computerized library.
What was his title then?
Well, he went through a bunch of titles.
He functioned in some ways as planning director.
He had one title was director for intergovernmental affairs and
His title and titles at HJC were frequently not exactly reflective of what people did.
When I was told he was planning director and went to look for a job there, I was told to speak to someone else who was director of special projects.
So it was always very confusing, at least in the early years, as to what this was.
And still the planning title was uneasy for a local government.
Frequently, in fact, when we were maybe doing some of our best planning, you'd never see anything called plan in something.
Anyway, the COG was involved in very sophisticated computerized things.
They were involved in the very early days of Landsat mapping, working with NASA and so forth.
They worked with David Birch from, I guess he was then with Harvard, Yale.

on what was called Recycum, and it was a very sophisticated simulation model that could spit out all kinds of demographics of every sort, which wound up being something of a fiasco because it got to be known as the Black Box, and it was one of those things where you never could figure out what went into it, and so what came out, you weren't too sure about.
But still, for planning at that time, it was very sophisticated.

I kind of grew up in the days of 208, the big waste treatment management planning, and though in those years the Houston plan was considered some disappointing, since it was in many areas very great compromise, in retrospect, I find that it really said some good things and was perhaps, you know, a forerunner to what we might now call strategic or policy planning.
But at that time, the concern of the local governments was that it say,
as little as possible, but be adequate to get certified so that the construction grants money would continue to flow.
I think one of the most important things that happened for the regional agency, NHGAC in particular, given the political surroundings and so forth, was when most of the federal money dried up.
And when there suddenly wasn't federal money, and we were talking about spending local,
dollars or soliciting contributions for specific work, the work became more part of the local government.
When did this transition occur?
This started happening in 80.
I guess the last of the 701 money was in 81.
And suddenly when we would present the budget, which was a program type budget, you know,
goals and objectives and this is what it'll take to reach it.
The board started coming up with ideas of things they wanted done.

The first thing that I was heavily involved with that was locally funded was in 79, beginning in 79 when we had some major floods in the area and the board said there must be something that HGAC could be doing to make sense of this problem.
And initially, it started from the fact that people were being evacuated from, say, Galveston and being sent to Colorado County.
And no one in Colorado County was told they were coming.
And there wasn't enough food.
And it was just kind of horrendous.
And it was then that HJC started to begin to evolve into the role of truly regional organizer or, I can't think of a good word now.
But we first did an emergency, well, it wound up being a directory for local officials in emergency preparedness or something.
And it was a step-by-step, here's what you do if the water is going to rise.
And it pulled together information from all kinds of places.
It presented elected officials a workbook they could put in their drawer where their city manager, whoever, would fill out the phone numbers that were right for that particular jurisdiction.
After that piece of work was concluded, they said, but we need to do more.
There's still this enormous flood problem, and it's clear that it might flood in Houston because of rains in Fort Bend County or in Brazoria because of rains in Harris County.
What can we do about this?
And so they asked us to do a study that had
well, two major goals.
One was who is really involved in flood control.
And secondly was kind of assess what current efforts were.
And what we discovered was that there were hundreds of local agencies, local, state, and federal agencies in this 113 county area who had responsibilities in flood control.
And nobody was talking to anybody.
There were virtually no joint projects going on between the two communities.
very little, and this was where you got into the local sticky politics, very little of what we call floodplain management, which tends to be land use management.
The report was very, very well received, and as a follow-on piece of work, more money, local money, was used to begin a flood control task force.
I don't know.
That wasn't what we called it.
We called it
It had sort of a nice name, I can't remember.
But it was, we got together the major actors in the 13 counties, and they sat at a table once a month, and they discussed flood control issues.

And a piece of work that they basically, the staff did under their direction, was to survey all of the communities and ask them what equipment and manpower and so forth they had that they would be willing to share with other communities, and what projects they might be willing to work on jointly.
It was very valuable from, if nothing else, from the extent that some of these people said, well, now I know who to call if I need help, which didn't exist before.
It was moving again towards this idea that in order for a region to survive, even if there's one major entity, you have to have coordination and cooperation.
And I think the COG began to evolve into understanding how communities work together.

that even in some work we did for HUD around the same time where HUD had an objective of moving, decentralizing public housing and moving people from one community to another, and all of which didn't make a whole lot of sense here because we just didn't have enough of it anywhere.
It wasn't a question of people being centralized.
And what we were able to do there was find that some of the smaller housing authorities
simply weren't equipped to do a good job of housing delivery.
And this happens a lot when you have one big community and a lot of little ones.

And we formed, again, an association of local housing authorities and got the housing authorities working together, which was the only way they could move towards this goal of allowing people movement within an area.
And the issue of the public housing on Allen Parkway is still with us, isn't it?
Yeah.
And it was interesting, in the course of that work, one of the more traumatic times of my public service, there were two schools of thought.
HUD was of the opinion that you were hurting minority and low-income people by keeping them bottled up in small concentrations.
Well, after they gave money...
